{"id":"2303.04610","submitter":"Przemek Mroz","authors":"P. Mroz, M. Ban, P. Marty, R. Poleski","title":"Free-floating or wide-orbit? Keck adaptive-optics observations reveal no\n  host stars near free-floating planet candidates","comments":"submitted to AAS Journals","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP astro-ph.GA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Recent detections of extremely short-timescale microlensing events imply the\nexistence of a large population of Earth- to Neptune-mass planets that appear\nto have no host stars. However, it is currently unknown whether these objects\nare truly free-floating planets or whether they are in wide orbits around a\ndistant host star. Here, we present the analysis of high-resolution imaging\nobservations of six free-floating planet candidates collected with the Keck\ntelescope. If these candidates were actually wide-orbit planets, the light of\nthe host would appear at a separation of 40-60 mas from the microlensing source\nstar. No such stars are detected. We carry out injection and recovery\nsimulations to estimate the sensitivity to putative host stars at different\nseparations. Depending on the object, the presented observations rule out\n10-35% of potential hosts assuming that the probability of hosting a planet\ndoes not depend on the host mass. If we assume that more massive stars are more\nlikely to host a planet, we rule out 18-63% of potential hosts. We argue that\ndeeper observations, for example with JWST, are needed to confidently confirm\nor refute the free-floating planet hypothesis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 8 Mar 2023 14:23:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-09"}
